

In recent weeks, the perilous nature of firefighting has been starkly highlighted by a series of tragic incidents. In Los Angeles, two firefighters are in critical condition, with several others injured following a devastating explosion. Meanwhile, in Karol Bagh, six firefighters sustained injuries from an LPG cylinder burst during intense firefighting operations. The dangers faced by these brave men and women are underscored by the grim statistic that six firefighters have lost their lives during rescue operations since 2016\. Adding to the toll, a forest fire in Almoraâ€™s Binsar Forest has claimed the lives of four firefighters and left four more injured while they bravely battled the blaze. These incidents serve as a sobering reminder of the risks inherent in firefighting and the valour of those who confront these dangers head-on.

* An estimated 65,650 firefighter injuries occurred in the line of duty in 2022, an increase of 8 percent from the 60,750 injuries reported in 2021\.

Firefighters were more likely to be injured at fire ground operations than during any other duties. In 2022, an estimated 21,325 injuries, or 33 percent of all reported firefighter injuries, occurred on the fire ground.
